│ the `ExtractElementInst` constructor, which is called from `Scatterer::operator[]`. The    │
│ assertion `isa<To>(Val)` fails, where `To` is `VectorType`. This means the `Scatterer` is  │
│ trying to create an `extractelement` instruction on a value that is not a vector.\n\n###   │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace is the most critical piece of information:\n\n-  │
│ `ScalarizerVisitor::visitExtractValueInst` is processing the `extractvalue`                │
│ instruction.\n-   Inside this function, it calls `Scatterer::operator[]`.\n-               │
│ `Scatterer::operator[]` is responsible for getting a scalar value (a single \"lane\") from │
│ a potentially vector or aggregate value.\n-   It attempts to do this by creating an        │
│ `extractelement` instruction.\n-   The value passed to `ExtractElementInst::Create` is not │
│ a vector, causing the `cast<VectorType>` to fail.\n\nBy inspecting the debugger state, we  │
│ can confirm that the value (`V`) inside the `Scatterer` at the time of the crash is the    │
│ `call` instruction `%t`, which has a struct type, not a vector type. The `Scatterer` was   │
│ asked to extract a scalar element from this struct as if it were a vector.\n\n### 3. Root  │
│ Cause Analysis\n\nThe `Scalarizer` pass uses a helper class called `Scatterer` to manage   │
│ the process of breaking down aggregate and vector values into their scalar                 │
│ components.\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how `Scatterer::operator[]` handles         │
│ different types of `Value*`. It has logic for vectors (it creates `extractelement`) and    │
│ scalars (it just returns the value). However, it lacks specific logic for                  │
│ `ExtractValueInst`.\n\nWhen `visitExtractValueInst` is called, it tries to find the scalar │
│ parts of the `extractvalue`'s result. It does so by creating a `Scatterer` for the         │
│ `extractvalue` instruction itself. When `Scatterer::operator[]` is then invoked, its       │
│ internal value `V` is this `ExtractValueInst`.\n\nSince there's no special handling for    │
│ `ExtractValueInst`, the code falls through to the part that assumes `V` is a vector. It    │
│ then tries to create an `extractelement` instruction using `V` as the vector operand. But  │
│ `V` is the `ExtractValueInst`, whose *type* is a vector, but the *value* itself is an      │
│ instruction. The `CreateExtractElement` function expects its first argument to be a        │
│ `Value*` whose *type* is a `VectorType`. The code incorrectly uses the                     │
│ `ExtractValueInst`'s aggregate operand (`%t`, the `call` instruction) as the vector to     │
│ extract from. Since `%t` has a struct type, the `cast<VectorType>` fails.\n\nThe correct   │
│ behavior would be for the `Scatterer` to recognize that it's dealing with an               │
│ `ExtractValueInst`, and recursively operate on the aggregate operand of that instruction,  │
│ adjusting the lane index to correctly pinpoint the scalar element within the nested        │
│ structure.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to add a new case to             │
│ `Scatterer::operator[]` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/Scalarizer.cpp` to specifically     │
│ handle `ExtractValueInst`. This new logic will:\n1.  Identify that the `Value*` (`V`) is   │
│ an `ExtractValueInst`.\n2.  Calculate the new lane index relative to the start of the      │
│ aggregate operand. This is done by summing the bit-sizes of the elements that come before  │
│ the one being extracted.\n3.  Update the `Scatterer`'s internal value `V` to be the        │
│ aggregate operand of the `ExtractValueInst`.\n4.  Recursively call `operator[]` with the   │
